it of hydrogen atom (Bohr radius) is approximately:", "explanation": "The Bohr radius a₀ is the radius of the first orbit (n = 1) of the hydrogen atom (Z = 1). Its value is a₀ = ε₀h²/(πme²) ≈ 0.529 Å = 0.529 × 10⁻¹⁰ m. This is a fundamental constant used as the unit of length in atomic physics.", "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr-02", "subtopic": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "topic_name": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "0.329 Å", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "0.529 Å", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "1.058 Å", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "2.116 Å", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This value is not standard. The Bohr radius is a well-known constant equal to 0.529 Å.", "misconception": "Recalling an incorrect numerical value"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "1.058 Å = 2 × 0.529 Å. This would be the radius of the first orbit for a hypothetical scenario, not the standard Bohr radius.", "misconception": "Doubling the Bohr radius inadvertently"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "2.116 Å = 4 × 0.529 Å = 0.529 × 2². This is actually the radius of the second Bohr orbit (n = 2) for hydrogen.", "misconception": "Confusing the second orbit radius with the first orbit radius"}]}, "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["bohr-radius", "hydrogen-atom", "first-orbit"]}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-atoms-nuclei", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "In Rutherford''s alpha-particle scattering experiment, most of the alpha particles pass through the gold foil without any deflection because:", "explanation": "Rutherford''s experiment showed that most alpha particles passed straight through the gold foil with little or no deflection. This is because most of the atom is empty space — the nucleus occupies an extremely small fraction (about 10⁻¹⁵ m in diameter compared to 10⁻¹⁰ m for the atom). Hence, most particles never come close to the nucleus.", "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr-03", "subtopic": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "topic_name": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "The nucleus has no charge", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Alpha particles are much heavier than gold atoms", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Most of the space inside an atom is empty", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "Alpha particles have very high kinetic energy", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "The gold nucleus has a charge of +79e. In fact, it is the nuclear charge that causes the deflection of those alpha particles that pass close to the nucleus.", "misconception": "Believing the nucleus is electrically neutral"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "Gold atoms (mass number 197) are actually much heavier than alpha particles (mass number 4). This is why alpha particles bounce back when they hit the nucleus head-on.", "misconception": "Reversing the relative masses of alpha particles and gold atoms"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "While alpha particles do have high kinetic energy, this alone does not explain why most pass undeflected. The reason is the emptiness of the atom.", "misconception": "Attributing undeflected passage to kinetic energy rather than atomic structure"}]}, "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["rutherford-scattering", "nuclear-model", "alpha-particle"]}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-atoms-nuclei", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "The Lyman series of the hydrogen spectrum lies in which region of the electromagnetic spectrum?", "explanation": "The Lyman series corresponds to transitions from higher energy levels (n₂ = 2, 3, 4, ...) to the ground state (n₁ = 1). These transitions involve the largest energy differences and produce photons in the ultraviolet region. The Balmer series lies in the visible region, while Paschen, Brackett, and Pfund series lie in the infrared region.", "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr-04", "subtopic": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "topic_name": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Visible region", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Infrared region", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "Microwave region", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "Ultraviolet region", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "The visible region corresponds to the Balmer series (transitions to n = 2), not the Lyman series.", "misconception": "Confusing Lyman series with Balmer series"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "The infrared region corresponds to the Paschen (n₁ = 3), Brackett (n₁ = 4), and Pfund (n₁ = 5) series.", "misconception": "Confusing Lyman series with Paschen/Brackett/Pfund series"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "Microwave radiation has much lower energy than the transitions in the hydrogen atom spectral series.", "misconception": null}]}, "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["lyman-series", "hydrogen-spectrum", "ultraviolet"]}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-atoms-nuclei", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The energy of an electron in the third Bohr orbit of hydrogen atom is:", "explanation": "The energy of an electron in the nth orbit of a hydrogen-like atom is Eₙ = −13.6Z²/n² eV. For hydrogen (Z = 1) in the third orbit (n = 3): E₃ = −13.6 × 1²/3² = −13.6/9 ≈ −1.51 eV.", "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr-05", "subtopic": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "topic_name": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "−3.40 eV", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "−1.51 eV", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "−0.85 eV", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "−13.6 eV", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "−3.40 eV = −13.6/4 = −13.6/2². This corresponds to n = 2 (second orbit), not n = 3.", "misconception": "Using n = 2 instead of n = 3"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "−0.85 eV = −13.6/16 = −13.6/4². This corresponds to n = 4 (fourth orbit), not n = 3.", "misconception": "Using n = 4 instead of n = 3"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "−13.6 eV is the energy of the ground state (n = 1). For n = 3, you must divide by n² = 9.", "misconception": "Forgetting to divide by n²"}]}, "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["energy-levels", "hydrogen-atom", "bohr-model"]}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-atoms-nuclei", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The ratio of the radii of the first three Bohr orbits of hydrogen atom is:", "explanation": "The radius of the nth Bohr orbit is rₙ = n²a₀/Z. For hydrogen (Z = 1): r₁ = a₀, r₂ = 4a₀, r₃ = 9a₀. Therefore, r₁ : r₂ : r₃ = 1 : 4 : 9, which follows the n² dependence.", "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr-06", "subtopic": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "topic_name": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "1 : 2 : 3", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "1 : 8 : 27", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "1 : 4 : 9", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "1 : 1/4 : 1/9", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "The ratio 1:2:3 corresponds to a linear (n) dependence. Bohr orbit radius depends on n², not n.", "misconception": "Assuming radius is proportional to n instead of n²"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "The ratio 1:8:27 corresponds to an n³ dependence. The radius depends on n², not n³.", "misconception": "Using n³ instead of n²"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This is the inverse-square ratio (1/n²). The radius increases as n², not decreases. This ratio describes how energy varies with n.", "misconception": "Confusing the energy level formula (−13.6/n²) with the radius formula (n²a₀)"}]}, "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["bohr-radius", "orbit-radius", "n-squared-dependence"]}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-atoms-nuclei", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The wavelength of the first line of the Balmer series of hydrogen is 656.3 nm. The wavelength of the second line of the Balmer series is approximately:", "explanation": "For the Balmer series, n₁ = 2. The first line: 1/λ₁ = R(1/4 − 1/9) = R(5/36). The second line: 1/λ₂ = R(1/4 − 1/16) = R(3/16). Therefore λ₂/λ₁ = (5/36)/(3/16) = (5 × 16)/(36 × 3) = 80/108 = 20/27. So λ₂ = 656.3 × (20/27) ≈ 486.1 nm.", "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr-07", "subtopic": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "topic_name": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "486.1 nm", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "434.0 nm", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "364.6 nm", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "410.2 nm", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "434.0 nm corresponds to the third Balmer line (n = 5 to n = 2), not the second line.", "misconception": "Selecting the wrong line of the series"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "364.6 nm is close to the series limit of the Balmer series (n = ∞ to n = 2), not the second line.", "misconception": "Confusing a specific line with the series limit"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "410.2 nm corresponds to the fourth Balmer line (n = 6 to n = 2), not the second line.", "misconception": "Selecting the wrong line of the series"}]}, "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["balmer-series", "ry