 orbit of hydrogen atom is v₁. The speed of the electron in the third orbit will be:", "explanation": "The speed of an electron in the nth Bohr orbit is given by vₙ = v₁Z/n. For hydrogen (Z = 1) in the third orbit (n = 3): v₃ = v₁/3. The electron speed decreases as 1/n because for larger orbits, the Coulomb force is weaker and the electron moves more slowly.", "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr-09", "subtopic": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "topic_name": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "3v₁", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "v₁/9", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "9v₁", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "v₁/3", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This suggests speed increases with n, but in Bohr''s model, the electron moves slower in higher orbits. Speed is inversely proportional to n.", "misconception": "Assuming speed increases with orbit number"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "v₁/9 = v₁/3² implies speed varies as 1/n². However, speed varies as 1/n, not 1/n².", "misconception": "Confusing 1/n dependence of velocity with 1/n² dependence of energy"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This would mean the speed increases as n², which contradicts Bohr''s model where higher orbits have lower speeds.", "misconception": "Confusing velocity with radius formula"}]}, "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["orbital-velocity", "bohr-model", "velocity-quantization"]}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-atoms-nuclei", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "The total number of spectral lines emitted when a hydrogen atom de-excites from the nth energy level to the ground state is given by n(n−1)/2. If a sample of hydrogen atoms is excited to the 4th energy level, how many spectral lines can be observed?", "explanation": "When hydrogen atoms are excited to the 4th energy level (n = 4), they can de-excite through various transitions. The total number of spectral lines = n(n−1)/2 = 4(4−1)/2 = 4 × 3/2 = 6. These lines correspond to transitions: 4→3, 4→2, 4→1, 3→2, 3→1, and 2→1.", "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr-10", "subtopic": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "topic_name": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "4", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "6", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "10", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "3", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This might come from thinking only about transitions from n = 4 directly to lower levels (4→3, 4→2, 4→1), but that gives only 3 lines from level 4. You must also count transitions between intermediate levels.", "misconception": "Counting only transitions originating from the highest level"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "10 = 5(5−1)/2, which would be the answer for n = 5, not n = 4.", "misconception": "Using the wrong value of n in the formula"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "3 counts only the direct transitions from n = 4 (to n = 3, 2, and 1), ignoring transitions like 3→2, 3→1, and 2→1.", "misconception": "Counting only transitions from the highest level to each lower level"}]}, "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["spectral-lines", "energy-transitions", "hydrogen-spectrum"]}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-atoms-nuclei", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "The radius of the innermost orbit of a hydrogen atom is 0.53 Å. The radius of the third orbit of He⁺ ion is:", "explanation": "The radius of the nth orbit for a hydrogen-like atom is rₙ = n²a₀/Z. For He⁺ ion (Z = 2) in the third orbit (n = 3): r₃ = 3² × 0.53/2 = 9 × 0.53/2 = 4.77/2 = 2.385 Å ≈ 2.38 Å. The radius increases as n² but decreases as 1/Z.", "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr-11", "subtopic": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "topic_name": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "4.77 Å", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "0.265 Å", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "1.06 Å", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "2.38 Å", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "4.77 Å = 9 × 0.53 Å is the radius of the third orbit of hydrogen (Z = 1). For He⁺, you must also divide by Z = 2.", "misconception": "Forgetting to account for Z in the radius formula for hydrogen-like ions"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "0.265 Å = 0.53/2 is the first Bohr orbit radius of He⁺. This does not account for n = 3.", "misconception": "Using n = 1 instead of n = 3"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "1.06 Å = 2 × 0.53 Å. This might result from using n = 2 for hydrogen or an incorrect formula.", "misconception": "Arithmetic error or using wrong quantum number"}]}, "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["hydrogen-like-atom", "orbit-radius", "helium-ion"]}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-atoms-nuclei", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "mcq", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Which of the following transitions in a hydrogen atom produces a photon of the shortest wavelength?", "explanation": "Shorter wavelength means higher energy of the emitted photon. The energy of a photon emitted during a transition is ΔE = 13.6(1/n₁² − 1/n₂²) eV. The transition n = 2 to n = 1 gives ΔE = 13.6(1 − 1/4) = 13.6 × 3/4 = 10.2 eV. The transition n = 5 to n = 4 gives ΔE = 13.6(1/16 − 1/25) = 13.6 × 9/400 = 0.306 eV. The transition n = 6 to n = 5 gives ΔE = 13.6(1/25 − 1/36) = 13.6 × 11/900 = 0.166 eV. The transition n = 3 to n = 2 gives ΔE = 13.6(1/4 − 1/9) = 13.6 × 5/36 = 1.89 eV. The largest energy difference (10.2 eV) corresponds to n = 2 → n = 1, giving the shortest wavelength.", "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr-12", "subtopic": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "topic_name": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "n = 2 to n = 1", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "n = 5 to n = 4", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "n = 6 to n = 5", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "n = 3 to n = 2", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "Transitions between high-n levels involve very small energy differences because energy levels get closer together at higher n. This gives a long wavelength.", "misconception": "Thinking higher quantum numbers give shorter wavelengths"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The transition n = 6 to n = 5 involves the smallest energy gap among all the options, producing the longest wavelength photon.", "misconception": "Confusing longest and shortest wavelength"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "While this transition (first Balmer line) has a significant energy gap, it is much smaller than the n = 2 to n = 1 transition (10.2 eV vs 1.89 eV).", "misconception": null}]}, "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["energy-transition", "photon-wavelength", "lyman-series"]}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-atoms-nuclei", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion_reasoning", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Assertion (A): The Bohr model successfully explains the spectra of hydrogen and hydrogen-like atoms but fails for multi-electron atoms.\nReason (R): The Bohr model does not account for electron-electron interactions and treats the problem as a single-electron system.", "explanation": "The Assertion is correct — the Bohr model works well for single-electron systems (H, He⁺, Li²⁺, etc.) but fails for multi-electron atoms like helium. The Reason is also correct and correctly explains why: the Bohr model considers only the Coulomb interaction between the nucleus and one electron, ignoring electron-electron repulsion. In multi-electron atoms, inter-electronic repulsion significantly affects energy levels, and the Bohr model has no provision for this. Hence both A and R are correct, and R is the correct explanation of A.", "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr-13", "subtopic": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "topic_name": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The Reason directly addresses why the Bohr model fails for multi-electron atoms — it ignores electron-electron interactions. This is the actual cause, making R the correct explanation of A.", "misconception": "Failing to see the causal link between electron-electron interaction and the model''s failure for multi-electron atoms"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The Reason is factually correct. The Bohr model indeed treats only one electron interacting with the nucleus and has no mechanism for electron-electron repulsion.", "misconception": "Incorrectly believing the Bohr model accounts for electron-electron interactions"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The Assertion is a well-established fact. The Bohr model accurately predicts spectra of H, He⁺, Li²⁺ but not of He, Li, etc.", "misconception": "Incorrectly thinking the Bohr model works for all atoms"}]}, "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["bohr-model-limitations", "multi-electron-atoms", "electron-interaction"]}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-atoms-nuclei", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "assertion_reasoning", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Assertion (A): In the Bohr model, the electron in a hydrogen atom does not radiate energy while revolving in a stationary orbit, even though it is an accelerating charge.\nReason (R): According to classical electromagnetic theory, an accelerating charged particle always radiates energy.", "explanation": "The Assertion is correct — Bohr''s second postulate explicitly states that electrons in stationary orbits do not radiate energy despite undergoing centripetal acceleration. This was a revolutionary departure from classical theory. The Reason is also correct — classical electromagnetic theory (Larmor formula) does predict that accelerating charges radiate energy. However, the Reason actually contradicts (or at least does not explain) the Assertion. Bohr''s postulate was introduced precisely to override this classical prediction. The Reason explains why the Bohr model had to introduce this postulate, but it does not explain why the electron does not radiate — it merely states the classical expectation. Both statements are true but R does not correctly explain A; rather, A is a postulate that overrides the classical prediction in R.", "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr-14", "subtopic": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "topic_name": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "bloom_level": "evaluate", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "Both A and R are correct and R is the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "Both A and R are correct but R is NOT the correct explanation of A", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "A is correct but R is incorrect", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "A is incorrect but R is correct", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "R states the classical prediction that accelerating charges radiate, but A says the electron does NOT radiate. R describes what classical theory predicts (radiation), which is opposite to what A claims (no radiation). R cannot be the explanation of A.", "misconception": "Assuming R explains A when R actually describes the classical expectation that Bohr''s postulate overrides"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "The Reason is factually correct. Classical electromagnetic theory does predict that accelerating charges radiate energy (Larmor formula). This is a well-established result.", "misconception": "Confusing the Bohr postulate with classical electromagnetic theory"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "The Assertion is correct. It is a direct statement of Bohr''s second postulate about stationary orbits.", "misconception": "Thinking Bohr''s postulate is incorrect"}]}, "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["bohr-postulates", "stationary-orbits", "classical-electrodynamics", "accelerating-charge"]}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-atoms-nuclei", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match_the_following", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "Match Column I (Spectral series) with Column II (Lower energy level n₁):\n\nColumn I: (P) Lyman series, (Q) Balmer series, (R) Paschen series, (S) Brackett series\n\nColumn II: (1) n₁ = 3, (2) n₁ = 1, (3) n₁ = 4, (4) n₁ = 2", "explanation": "The spectral series of hydrogen are named after their discoverers and are defined by the lower energy level: Lyman series has n₁ = 1 (UV region), Balmer series has n₁ = 2 (visible region), Paschen series has n₁ = 3 (IR region), Brackett series has n₁ = 4 (IR region). Therefore: P→2, Q→4, R→1, S→3.", "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr-15", "subtopic": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "topic_name": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "P→1, Q→2, R→3, S→4", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "P→2, Q→1, R→4, S→3", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "P→2, Q→4, R→1, S→3", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "P→4, Q→2, R→3, S→1", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This option assigns P (Lyman) to n₁ = 3, but the Lyman series corresponds to transitions to n₁ = 1, the ground state.", "misconception": "Not knowing that Lyman series terminates at the ground state"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "This swaps the Balmer and Paschen series assignments. Balmer corresponds to n₁ = 2 (not 1) and Paschen to n₁ = 3 (not 4).", "misconception": "Confusing the order of spectral series"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "This assigns Lyman to n₁ = 4 and Brackett to n₁ = 1, which is reversed. Lyman is the first series (n₁ = 1) and Brackett is the fourth (n₁ = 4).", "misconception": "Reversing the order of spectral series"}]}, "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["spectral-series", "hydrogen-spectrum", "energy-transitions"]}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-atoms-nuclei", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "match_the_following", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "Match Column I (Physical quantity in Bohr model) with Column II (Dependence on principal quantum number n for hydrogen atom):\n\nColumn I: (P) Orbital radius, (Q) Electron speed, (R) Total energy, (S) Time period of revolution\n\nColumn II: (1) Proportional to n³, (2) Proportional to n², (3) Inversely proportional to n², (4) Inversely proportional to n", "explanation": "In the Bohr model for hydrogen (Z = 1): Orbital radius rₙ ∝ n² (P→2). Electron speed vₙ ∝ 1/n (Q→4). Total energy Eₙ = −13.6/n² ∝ −1/n², so |Eₙ| ∝ 1/n² (R→3). Time period Tₙ = 2πrₙ/vₙ ∝ n²/(1/n) = n³ (S→1). Therefore the correct matching is P→2, Q→4, R→3, S→1.", "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr-16", "subtopic": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "topic_name": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "bloom_level": "analyze", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "P→2, Q→3, R→4, S→1", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "P→1, Q→4, R→3, S→2", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "P→2, Q→4, R→1, S→3", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "P→2, Q→4, R→3, S→1", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "This assigns Q (electron speed) to 1/n² and R (energy) to 1/n. Speed varies as 1/n, not 1/n², and energy magnitude varies as 1/n², not 1/n.", "misconception": "Swapping the n-dependence of speed and energy"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "This assigns P (radius) to n³ and S (time period) to n². Radius varies as n² and time period as n³, not the other way around.", "misconception": "Confusing the n-dependence of radius and time period"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "This assigns R (energy) to n³ and S (time period) to 1/n². Energy magnitude varies as 1/n² and time period as n³.", "misconception": "Incorrectly matching energy and time period dependencies"}]}, "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["bohr-model", "quantum-number-dependence", "orbital-properties"]}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-atoms-nuclei", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true_false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "In Bohr''s model of the hydrogen atom, the frequency of radiation emitted when an electron jumps from a higher orbit to a lower orbit equals the difference in energy of the two orbits divided by Planck''s constant.", "explanation": "This is TRUE. According to Bohr''s frequency condition (third postulate), when an electron transitions from a higher energy level E₂ to a lower energy level E₁, a photon is emitted with frequency ν = (E₂ − E₁)/h, where h is Planck''s constant. This is a direct statement of energy conservation: the photon carries away the exact energy difference between the two levels.", "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr-17", "subtopic": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "topic_name": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "bloom_level": "remember", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "B", "hint": "The statement is a direct expression of Bohr''s third postulate: hν = E₂ − E₁, which gives ν = (E₂ − E₁)/h. This is a fundamental result.", "misconception": "Confusing Bohr''s frequency condition with some other relationship"}]}, "correct_answer": "A", "concept_tags": ["bohr-frequency-condition", "photon-emission", "energy-conservation"]}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-atoms-nuclei", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "true_false", "difficulty": "easy", "question_text": "In the Bohr model, the electron in a hydrogen atom can revolve in any orbit as long as its energy is negative.", "explanation": "This is FALSE. In the Bohr model, the electron cannot revolve in any arbitrary orbit. It can only exist in specific quantized orbits where the angular momentum is an integral multiple of h/2π (i.e., L = nh/2π where n = 1, 2, 3, ...). This quantization condition restricts the electron to only certain discrete orbits, not all orbits with negative energy.", "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr-18", "subtopic": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "topic_name": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "bloom_level": "understand", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "True", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "False", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "C", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "---", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "The key feature of Bohr''s model is quantization — the electron is restricted to specific orbits where L = nh/2π. A continuous range of orbits with negative energy would be the classical model, which Bohr rejected.", "misconception": "Confusing the classical model (continuous orbits) with Bohr''s quantized model"}]}, "correct_answer": "B", "concept_tags": ["quantized-orbits", "bohr-postulates", "angular-momentum"]}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-atoms-nuclei", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "fill_in_the_blanks", "difficulty": "medium", "question_text": "The maximum number of spectral lines that can be emitted when a hydrogen atom in the 5th excited state de-excites to the ground state is _____.", "explanation": "The 5th excited state corresponds to n = 6 (since the ground state is n = 1, the first excited state is n = 2, and so on). The number of spectral lines emitted when an atom de-excites from level n to the ground state is n(n−1)/2 = 6(6−1)/2 = 6 × 5/2 = 15. These arise from all possible downward transitions between levels 6, 5, 4, 3, 2, and 1.", "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr-19", "subtopic": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "topic_name": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "bloom_level": "apply", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "10", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "5", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "15", "is_correct": true}, {"key": "D", "text": "6", "is_correct": false}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "10 = 5(5−1)/2, which would apply if the atom were in the 4th excited state (n = 5). The 5th excited state is n = 6.", "misconception": "Confusing the excited state number with the principal quantum number (n = 5 is the 4th excited state, not the 5th)"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "5 would be the number of direct transitions from n = 6 to lower levels (6→5, 6→4, 6→3, 6→2, 6→1), ignoring intermediate transitions.", "misconception": "Counting only transitions from the highest level"}, {"option_key": "D", "hint": "6 = 4(4−1)/2, which applies to n = 4 (3rd excited state). The 5th excited state has n = 6.", "misconception": "Using the wrong principal quantum number"}]}, "correct_answer": "C", "concept_tags": ["spectral-lines", "excited-state", "de-excitation"]}, {"chapter_id": "cuet-phy-atoms-nuclei", "topic_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr", "exam_ids": ["CUET", "NEET"], "question_type": "scenario_based", "difficulty": "hard", "question_text": "A research team is studying a distant star''s atmosphere by analyzing its absorption spectrum. They observe a series of dark lines corresponding to the Balmer series of hydrogen. The wavelength of the line corresponding to the transition from n = 4 to n = 2 is measured to be 486.1 nm. Using the Rydberg formula, if the Rydberg constant R = 1.097 × 10⁷ m⁻¹, calculate the wavelength of the Balmer series limit (n = ∞ to n = 2) and identify its spectral region.", "explanation": "The Balmer series limit corresponds to the transition from n₂ = ∞ to n₁ = 2. Using the Rydberg formula: 1/λ = R(1/n₁² − 1/n₂²) = R(1/4 − 1/∞) = R/4. Therefore λ = 4/R = 4/(1.097 × 10⁷) = 3.646 × 10⁻⁷ m = 364.6 nm. This wavelength (364.6 nm) lies in the ultraviolet region of the electromagnetic spectrum, just below the visible violet limit (~380 nm). The Balmer series limit marks the shortest wavelength (highest energy) transition in the Balmer series.", "payload": {"question_id": "cuet-phy-atom-bohr-20", "subtopic": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "topic_name": "Bohr Model and Hydrogen Spectrum", "bloom_level": "evaluate", "options": [{"key": "A", "text": "656.3 nm, visible region", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "B", "text": "121.5 nm, ultraviolet region", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "C", "text": "820.4 nm, infrared region", "is_correct": false}, {"key": "D", "text": "364.6 nm, ultraviolet region", "is_correct": true}], "elimination_hints": [{"option_key": "A", "hint": "656.3 nm is the wavelength of the first Balmer line (Hα, n = 3 to n = 2), not the series limit. The series limit has the shortest wavelength in the series.", "misconception": "Confusing the first line of the Balmer series with the series limit"}, {"option_key": "B", "hint": "121.5 nm corresponds to the Lyman-α line (n = 2 to n = 1), not the Balmer series limit. This is in the far UV.", "misconception": "Confusing Lyman series transitions with Balmer series limit"}, {"option_key": "C", "hint": "820.4 nm lies in the infrared region. The Balmer series lies in the visible-to-near-UV region, with the series limit at 364.6 nm.", "misconception": "Using an incorrect formula or confusing with the Paschen series"}]}, "correct_answer": "D", "concept_tags": ["rydberg-formula", "balmer-series-limit", "spectral-analysis", "stellar-spectroscopy"]}]'::jsonb, 'cuet-physics', 'json-seed-batch-1');

